artwork.description: '' A Kashmiri Midsummer Day's Dream'' inspired by a dear friend's visit to Shill Villa, a lovely house in Srinagar that was our home for a couple of years, and by the beauty and culture of the Kashmir Valley; in Kashmir,the stuff you see outdoors, the flora n fauna, Nature's beauty at her best, are painstakingly handcrafted indoors,reflecting in the paper mache artefacts, the rugs, the samovar, the aari work embroidery by the art-loving people. Art was and still is in the blood of the people here, before blood came to stain the arts for a not-so-brief patch... The lady in the art work is a friend, Garima who had come visiting us in ''Raazi House'' as we call it as key scenes of the Bollywood film, Raazi had been shot here. The pretty pose Garima struck as she had a pic taken before a beautiful bower of roses, the defining feature of Raazi House, set in motion the conceptual idea of the work- Garima on a magical carpet, flying over the beautiful vale and the beautiful vale and the details kept adding themselves.

Invincible Summer

Standing tall and yellow...the ‘Amaltas  tree’
Remembering how hard the world pushes against you,there is something stronger and brighter pushing you right back.....within us...around us...
So look around.....
Seek your inspiration  from nature.

artwork.description: This painting portrays Greeshm Ritu - the summer season. Forests are burning, trees are charred, earth is parched, and dry leaves are flying in the hot winds.                                                                                         Some 1500 years ago, the great ancient poet Kaalidaas wrote a lyrical poem named Ritu-Sanhaar in Sanskrit language. Ritu-Sanhaar means description of seasons. Kaalidaas divided the year in six seasons. Season means Ritu. The six seasons are Greeshm Ritu (4th may-30th june), Varsha Ritu (1st july-12th sept), Sharad Ritu (13th sept-26th oct), Hemant Ritu (27th oct-24th dec), Shishir Ritu (25th dec-4th mar), and Vasant Ritu (5th mar-3rd may).                                                                                    Over the years I have recorded my observations of nature including flowers, trees, birds, festivals and cultural activities in India.                                Paintings in Ritu-Sanhaar series are portrayal of Kaalidaas's writings and my observations.

artwork.description:
Sunil Kale is a Satara based celebrated impressionist artist; his artworks are a natural retreat to experience the various moods of nature. His proximity to the natural beauty has allowed him capture nature at its best time and again.
 Sunil says “It is an expression of my heart, which depicts the stunning beauty of nature. Sometimes it is mysterious & scary, and the choked expression erupts .It is an outburst of forms, it is an extravaganza of colours, it is mingling and mixing of shades & tints. It is my spontaneous work of art. A painting that engulfs my mind with sheer pleasure”

artwork.description: Benares is known as abode of salvation which imparts the salvation to any sensitive human soul. It truly depicts eternal grandeur on this earth. Latest creative work by Reba Mandal illustrates her ode to the beauty of Banaras Ghats, Ganga Ghats and other spiritual environment in picturesque form. She has shown Ganga Ghats at Varanasi which are fully of pilgrims, temples and prayers. She has shown boats, temples and sandstones/pebbles at the lower arena of the work symbolising her serene and fast thinking mindscape. Her skills and command over the medium used are also seen in tonal harmony and rhythm of apt colour schemes. She has shown Ganga Ghats at Varanasi that compliment the concept of divinity
